TrevDay:

any tips for cadding wires? at what point does 3005 design the electrical system?

Great timing for you, in 20 minutes @Orion.DeYoe will be giving a talk on exactly this at the New England Mentor Conference, titled “You Should CAD Your Wires”:

During the 2025 season, FRC 3005, the RoboChargers, debuted a highly effective workflow for laying out and routing the robot’s electrical subsystem early in the design process. This presentation will review how this workflow helped FRC 3005 streamline the robot build process and improve reliability and maintainability. The workflow builds on the success of their “High Fidelity Block CAD” methodology. The presentation includes a first look at several custom Onshape features developed by RoboChargers members to streamline this part of the design process.

It will be livestreamed as well.

posts.name: Greyson Long
posts.cooked:
Well, we obviously didnt design with climbing the reef in mind. But, the coral ejector structure was primarily carbon fiber tube and MaxComposite. So that mechanism was quite strong in tension. Generally, all that would happen as a reault of climbing the reef was that the laterator would derail. Now, over time, the laterator did get looser left to right, so we did have to shim it for our offseason event to keep it from derailing under normal operation.

Orion, who has presented on the topic at mentor conferences, introduced Block CAD to the team when he joined and it just worked perfectly for us. Ito better understand the benefits of the Block CAD method, i would highly recommend you watch his presentation on it from last year’s mentor conference.

posts.name: Greyson Long
posts.cooked:
TrevDay:

how is this sprocket (7A12) manufactured? if aluminum or polycarb, did you do any post-machining filing on the edges? if 3dp, how well did it hold up over the season?

That sprocket is 3D printed in PLA, and we didn’t have any issues with it failing. It wasn’t a high torque joint, that’s the thing. Also, for 3D printing gears, sprockets, or pulleys, the inportant thing is to set the number of walls high enough that the teeth are completely solid.

TrevDay:

I didn’t see many teams use a continuous chain elevator, was chain selected based on experience or were there other factors involved in the decision?

We chose chain mostly due to familiarity with it.

TrevDay:

3005 used a ton of maxcomposite on this robot, any particular insights on effectively using it?

In general, you can use MaxComposite in much the same way as polycarbonate. The most important part is proper manufacturing - laser cutting is best, but you can use a router, you just need to melt the edges so they seal the woven layers. One key difference is that MaxComposite, like other woven composites, is not well suited for edge loading, it will delaminate.

posts.name: Greyson Long
posts.cooked: We didn’t really see much issue with these. They started out as Markforged Onyx parts, but we switched to MaxComposite for weight reduction. We maybe only replaced one of the Onxy version due to failure, but it wasn’t a sudden or catastrophic failure. It just deformed over time.

posts.name: Greyson Long
posts.cooked:
It varies year to year, but we usually aim to have Block CAD 90% done within a week or week and a half after kickoff. There are sometimes some finishing touches on a subsytem that dont gate other subsystems that account for the last 10%.

Detail CAD time varies as well of course. This year, I think we “finished” the first full robot assembly design about 2.5 or 3 weeks after kickoff. But there were continuous revisions all the way up to World Champs.

Historically, we have not generally done much prototyping and this year was no exception. So, we mostly just with with “gut feel” for block CAD and made iterations as necessary.
